  "tutorial/testing::section-0008": {
    "node_id": "tutorial/testing::section-0008",
    "parent_id": "tutorial/testing::section-0006",
    "level": 3,
    "node_kind": "heading",
    "heading_text": "Extended testing file",
    "anchor_id": "extended-testing-file",
    "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/testing/#extended-testing-file",
    "section_text": "You could then update test_main.py with the extended tests:\n\nWhenever you need the client to pass information in the request and you don't know how to, you can search (Google) how to do it in httpx , or even how to do it with requests , as HTTPX's design is based on Requests' design.\n\nThen you just do the same in your tests.\n\nE.g.:\n\n- To pass a path or query parameter, add it to the URL itself.\n\n- To pass a JSON body, pass a Python object (e.g. a dict ) to the parameter json .\n\n- If you need to send Form Data instead of JSON, use the data parameter instead.\n\n- To pass headers , use a dict in the headers parameter.\n\n- For cookies , a dict in the cookies parameter.\n\nFor more information about how to pass data to the backend (using httpx or the TestClient ) check the HTTPX documentation .",
    "section_inline_code": [
      "test_main.py",
      "httpx",
      "requests",
      "dict",
      "json",
      "data",
      "headers",
      "cookies",
      "TestClient"
    ],
    "section_links": [
      {
        "text": "HTTPX documentation",
        "url": "https://www.python-httpx.org",
        "section_id": "tutorial/testing::section-0008",
        "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/testing/#extended-testing-file"
      }
    ],
    "code_refs": [
      {
        "type": "code_ref",
